nce 1800. She investigates cultural phenomena such as blue laws and the Sunday newspaper, alongside representations of Sunday in the popular arts. Holy Day, Holiday attends to the history of religion, as well as the histories of labor, leisure, and domesticity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aRestxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesy19th century. 0aRestxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesy20th century. 0aSundayxHistory of doctrinesy19th century. 0aSundayxHistory of doctrinesy20th century. 0aWeekly rest-dayzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWeekly rest-dayzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501728686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501728686.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG